How Yelp C.E.O. Jeremy Stoppelman Created a Revolutionary Product | Vanity FairVanity FairSign InIn The DetailsWhat You Should Know About Jeremy StoppelmanA panoply of eccentric biographical data re: the ur-yelper.by David KampOctober 2014EmailFacebookTwitterJeremy Stoppelman, photographed in San Francisco.He was just another gangly Web 2.0 kid with a good job in Silicon Valley (at PayPal) and a big dream: in his case, to launch an online successor to the Yellow Pages. But something funny happened shortly after Jeremy Stoppelman’s project, Yelp, went live: its users embraced the site’s “Write a review” feature to a degree far greater than anticipated. A few weeks of hasty re-coding later, Yelp was reconfigured to make reviewing its raison d’être, and Stoppelman has never looked back. Ten years after its founding, Yelp is the Web’s premier site and app for customer reviews—not just of restaurants, but of shops, kiosks, food trucks, parks, bus lines, funeral homes, D.M.V. offices, and even human attractions. (The Naked Cowboy in Times Square was averaging four stars out of five at press time.) Herewith, some info gleaned from a meandering conversation with the Yelp C.E.O., who turns 37 this November.HE IS himself an avid Yelper, reviewing under the profile name Big Papa. He has waxed enthusiastic over the Renaissance Salon in his current hometown of San Francisco (“My last haircut generated mucho complimentos” ) and panned Frankfurt’s airport (an “authentic interpretation of Dante’s Inferno” ).AMONG THE happiest discoveries he has made by perusing Yelp reviews is the existence of the Seward Street Slides, in San Francisco’s Castro district. “It’s basically these two concrete slides in a quiet, residential neighborhood,” he says. “You zip down them sitting on top of flattened cardboard boxes. I’d be curious to learn the history of these slides, because they’re, like, not at all safe.”HE INITIALLY resisted the push to name his company Yelp, because, to him, it sounded like “a sad cry for help.” He preferred the name Yocal (rhyming with “local” ).HE GREW up in the Virginia suburbs of Washington, D.C., the son of a securities lawyer and a teacher, and attended Langley High School, just down the road from the headquarters of the C.I.A. Among his schoolmates were a son of Antonin Scalia’s and some kids who were curiously vague about what their parents did for a living.__HE IS—__notwithstanding the fact that Google’s autocomplete function suggests the words “Jeremy Stoppelman Indian” when you enter his name into the search field—a Jewish American of European ancestry who attended a Reform temple as a child and had a Bar Mitzvah. He attributes the frequent misperception of his ethnicity to his “black hair and dark skin tone.”HE PLAYED tennis as a youth and was often told that he looked like Pete Sampras.__HIS FIRST__computer—his family’s, actually—was an Amiga 2000, a little-remembered late-80s high-end P.C. with “unbelievable sound and graphics capabilities” that, to this day, he feels doesn’t get its due.HIS YOUNGER brother, Michael, is Yelp’s vice president in charge of engineering. His older brother, Andy, two years his senior, died abruptly on the eve of his high-school graduation, in 1993, of a rare heart-rhythm disorder. That experience, Jeremy says, made him realize that “life is very short and you have to make the most of it.”HE IS frequently vilified by critics who claim that Yelp is a protection racket whose sales representatives shake down small-business owners, offering better placement of positive reviews (and/or the burying of negative reviews) in exchange for ad purchases—a charge that Stoppelman flatly denies, noting that all the lawsuits brought against Yelp to this effect have been dismissed.HE WAS called a “scumbag,” a “dick,” and “full of shit,” among other things, when he participated in a Reddit Ask Me Anything session last year. He did not respond in kind.HE ACCEPTS the invective hurled his way as the cost of creating a “disruptive, game-changing service or product,” likening the heat Yelp takes to that felt by Airbnb (vis-à-vis the hotel industry) and Uber (vis-à-vis the taxicab industry).HE HAS met three current or former heads of state: two U.S. presidents, Barack Obama and Bill Clinton, and the Taoiseach of Ireland, Enda Kenny.HE TOOK up guitar playing just a couple of years ago. He has mastered “Banana Pancakes,” by Jack Johnson. He is getting there on Eric Clapton’s “Layla.”HE FINDS conventional guitar pop difficult to code to, since it interrupts his thought process, but maintains that “the pulsating beat of electronic music is actually very focusing.” Back when he was frequently coding, his favorite artist was the house-music D.J.and producer Kaskade.HE HAS taken to preaching online about the dangers of sugar, citing the research of the outspoken pediatric endocrinologist Robert Lustig (of the University of California, San Francisco) and arguing that “a sugar tax isn’t a terrible idea.”THAT SAID, Yelp user Big Papa recently gave four stars to the San Francisco bakery Baked, describing its brownie as “a complete gut bomb, but it delivered the fructose and glucose I needed to get through a really long end of day meeting.”Jeremy StoppelmanFOLLOWBarack ObamaFOLLOWFollow to get the latest news and analysis about the players in your inbox.See All PlayersShareEmailFacebookTwitterDavid KampDavid Kamp has been a Vanity Fair contributing editor since 1996, profiling such monumental figures of the arts as Johnny Cash, Lucian Freud, Sly Stone, and John Hughes.YOU MIGHT LIKEAN INTERACTIVE LIST OF THE 2014 NEW ESTABLISHMENTVanity FairAs the Mooch Vows to “Kill All the Leakers,” Spicer Receives a Hero’s Welcome in New YorkVanity FairWhy the Scariest Nuclear Threat May Be Coming from Inside the White HouseVanity Fair“I Want to F*cking Kill All the Leakers”: Scaramucci Explodes in Unhinged Late-Night RantVanity FairObamacare Repeal Dies in the Senate as McCain Twists the KnifeVanity