Yelp's Jeremy Stoppelman: a profile

1 / 3


Back to Gallery
















Jeremy Stoppelman was on a conference call with venture capitalists when an assistant slipped him a note: "Steve Jobs is on the line."
Stoppelman quietly left the room at Yelp headquarters in downtown San Francisco. It was January 2010, and Google wanted to buy Yelp, the online, crowd-sourced review site. 
On the phone, Jobs urged Stoppelman, who revered the Apple chief as a visionary, to "stay independent and not sell out to Google." Jobs was not a fan of Google and had accused the search giant of stealing Apple's smart-phone and tablet technology.
"At that point, we had already turned down Google," Stoppelman said. "But Steve liked Yelp and wanted to make sure about Google. It was a moment where I said, 'This is crazy. What just happened?' "



Latest news videos




 
For Stoppelman, who is 34 and co-founded Yelp in October 2004, the crazy moments have only continued. After his company went public this spring, when the young entrepreneur pushed the button to ring the opening bell on the New York Stock Exchange, Stoppelman received another call - this one from President Obama, congratulating him. 
Today, Yelp has a market capitalization of about $1.3 billion, and Stoppelman's 11 percent stake is valued at more than $145 million. The company, which started in San Francisco as a vague idea about "local," now has 70 million unique monthly visitors, and has expanded to 17 countries. Stoppelman is an undisputed junior titan of Silicon Valley.
Sought-after nerd
He also has the canonical startup story. He was the kid who loved to tinker, who inadvertently blew a few things up and charred the walls with his experiments, who learned programming in middle school, earned his bachelor's degree in computer engineering, and then headed west - arriving in San Francisco at the start of the dot-com boom. He was the kid who became a sought-after nerd and was - after his second job out of college - given $1 million to sit around a SoMa loft with a dozen people and a dog and dream up The Next Big Thing. 
"The rule in the incubator was that we'd play around and come up with crazy ideas," said Max Levchin, a Ukraine-born computer scientist who co-founded the online payment system PayPal, where Stoppelman worked as his second job out of college. "It was a hacker commune, and the idea was to build great products."
Levchin, whose PayPal was sold to eBay for $1.5 billion in 2002, remembers the day Stoppelman and another former PayPal engineer, Russ Simmons, landed on the concept that would become Yelp.
"It was my 29th birthday, and we were at the Slanted Door in the Ferry Building," Levchin said. "Jeremy and Russ had been talking about doing something with local review or local search and were asking questions like: How do you get your friends to help you find the best plumber or doctor or nicest restaurant close by? Over lunch, I could see Russ and Jeremy at the other end of the table just scheming. After lunch, they said they thought they'd figured it out."
Ranking of businesses
Returning to the incubator on Mission near Third Street, Levchin listened as Stoppelman and Simmons explained their inchoate idea of an "e-mail type of product where you ask your friends to help you come up with a ranking of businesses."
"I thought it might work, but it might not," Levchin said. "I backed them because I believed in Russ and Jeremy. Russ is an amazing developer and engineer, and Jeremy is just really smart and really tenacious, with a lot of good stubbornness. Their idea was good, but of course it was not what Yelp ended up being, which is very common with startups."
Elon Musk, another PayPal founder, said he always considered Yelp a cool idea. Musk had done something similar with a company called Zip2, which he founded after dropping out of Stanford graduate school to provide local online content to news organizations.
"Someone needed to do user reviews right," said Musk, who went on to run Tesla Motors and co-found SpaceX, which recently made history by having the first commercial spaceship complete a mission to the International Space Station. "Effectively, Yelp is fulfilling a much better function than the Yellow Pages ever did," Musk said. "What Jeremy did was come up with an unmet need to know about local businesses and services."
Stoppelman, who spent his early childhood in Arlington, Va., before his family moved to nearby McLean - his middle school was next to CIA headquarters - said his interest in computers started in the fifth grade.
His mother, Lynn, was an English teacher before she began a marketing business out of their home, and his father, John, was a securities lawyer. 
"I think my dad did legal work for someone who had a Packard Bell 8088, and they couldn't pay him so they gave him a computer," Stoppelman said, sitting in a Yelp conference room, his vizsla named Darwin at his side. "I was initially not allowed to touch it, but that didn't last long. I started tinkering with it, and there were many times I screwed up the computer."
He got his own personal computer, an Amiga 2000, when he was in the 10th grade, and he was soon convinced that he'd be a video game programmer when he grew up. In high school, he took programming classes in Turbo Pascal, a software development system.
But the young Stoppelman was equally interested in business and investing. His father took small companies public, and talked about stocks. Jeremy was 14 when he opened a Schwab account and bought stocks with money earned mowing lawns or picking up pinecones.
When he arrived at the University of Illinois, he was interested in both finance and engineering. He thought the business majors looked like they were having fun, and the engineering majors looked like they were enduring torture. He chose engineering and graduated in 1999. 
Arriving in the valley
"I was interviewing for jobs really as the bubble was getting started," Stoppelman said. When he came out for an interview at a startup called@Home Network, a high-speed cable Internet service, he was struck by what he saw driving to the interview.
"I was driving down (Highway) 101, and I'd see these billboards for engineering tools, like FPGA (an integrated circuit). I thought, this is a very hard-core place if people can afford billboards to advertise esoteric technologies that the average person would have no clue about."
Within three weeks of being hired as a software engineer at@Home, he'd finished his work and found there was nothing else for him to do. "I'd go to my boss and say I was done. He'd say, 'OK, come back at 5.' I'd come back, and he'd be gone. It was a messed-up company."
He stayed for four months, all the while having his phone "ring every day with recruiters."
"I thought it was stupid to be with a big company," Stoppelman said. "I found my way to X.com (the precursor to PayPal), where I interviewed with Elon Musk. I didn't know these guys existed yet: the 28-year-old CEO, this senior guy who has the crazy twinkle in his eye, and he's telling me how his company is going to take down Visa and MasterCard. I'd just never seen this before. I thought of companies as big organizations that hired gray-haired CEOs. I was like, 'Whoa, I want to learn from this guy!' So I ended up as the third engineer hired. I stayed for 3 1/2 years."
When eBay purchased PayPal, Stoppelman was ready for something different, and he enrolled at Harvard Business School.
"I came back to San Francisco for the summer after my first year at Harvard and was originally going to work for Peter Thiel (the third PayPal founder, who had started a hedge fund called Clarium Capital). We had been in touch, and he said, 'We'll find something for you to do.' So I went to his office and was filling out paperwork, and Peter said, 'I was talking to Max (Levchin), and he has this new incubator thing brewing. So I went over to 650 Mission, and Max said, 'Great, hang out here. Just brainstorm until you come up with something.' "
Stoppelman had every intention of returning to Harvard in the fall.
"Jeremy was doing well in business school, and his goal was to get under his belt the basics of business theory so he could be a well-rounded CEO to start his own company," Levchin recalled. But "when Jeremy and Russ had this idea that came together over my birthday lunch, I said to Jeremy, 'You can hit the snooze button on the alarm clock of life, or this can be the big alarm.' I told him he was ready, and that this was a huge opportunity that - if he hit the snooze button - it would go away."
Stoppelman said, "When Max committed $1 million to us, to basically two guys with an idea, we had our 'Are you for real? Or are you a phony?' moment."
Stoppelman dropped out of Harvard. When Yelp was started in 2004, it was a social network built around asking friends for recommendations. 
"We got some early press on it," Stoppelman said, "but mostly people said it's a cool concept but in practice, it's still easier just to e-mail your friends directly." While disappointed, Stoppelman and Simmons began to look at how people had used the new site. They landed on something interesting.
A change in plans
"We had added a feature literally as an afterthought," Stoppelman said. "Russ asked me, 'Should we have a way people can write a review without being asked a question?' I said, 'Sure, no one is going to use it, but sure, tuck it in there.' What we found after the failed launch was that writing reviews was popular. We realized we had missed something there. We began to build a new site that was all about making review writing fun."
The new Yelp was launched in February 2005 and began to take off immediately. By June 2006, it had 1 million unique visitors per month.
"The site became popular in San Francisco, but then came the question of scalability," Stoppelman recalled. "People told us, 'Oh, this will work in San Francisco but not in a place like New York.' "
 Yelp was rolled out in Boston, then Chicago, then Los Angeles and New York. Very early on, they hit on the idea of a "Yelp Elite Squad," where the most prolific Yelpers were invited to social events. The gatherings, held sometimes once a week at bars and restaurants, turned an online experience into a community of like minds.
The problem Yelp faces today, Stoppelman noted, is the same problem that Google faces in its rankings. Several lawsuits have been filed by business owners against Yelp reviewers, and allegations of illegitimate reviews have dogged the company.
"You are going to have people who are unhappy with the reviews or the placement," Stoppelman said. "Rest assured, our engineers are working every day to make sure reviews are unbiased and accurate."
Daily routine unchanged
On a recent day, Stoppelman, who is unmarried and lives in the Marina, heads out on a walk along Crissy Field with Darwin. In slim-fitting jeans, slim blazer, a checked button-down and aviator shades, he said that while his life is dotted with crazy moments - the calls from Steve Jobs or the president - his daily existence hasn't changed much. 
His small desk at work is set in the midst of everyone else's. He still likes checking out new bars and restaurants, is a voracious reader of nonfiction (a recent book was "Moonwalking With Einstein: The Art and Science of Remembering Everything"), and he's taking an online course to learn how to play the guitar. His 30-year-old brother, Michael, is vice president of engineering at Yelp. And his mother was recently out for a visit. (His father died in 1998.)
Walking along the windswept path of Crissy Field, Stoppelman said he is looking now at "how big Yelp can be. We are a successful U.S. company. But can we be global? Will the things that work here work in Japan? In China? They all represent a different challenge."
Looking out at the sweeping Golden Gate Bridge, Stoppelman said, "As a kid, I harbored this fantasy of starting a company. I looked at the entrepreneur column in Forbes. I looked at it every month and thought, 'I want to be that guy.' "
The day Yelp went public is a day he'll never forget.
"It was this euphoric feeling of pushing the button to turn on the bell, and it was like that moment on the roller coaster going cha-ching, cha-ching, cha-ching, and then I'm on 'Squawk Box' and Jim Cramer is yelling at me and three panelists are hitting me with questions. It was high stress, but fun. My mom was up there with me on the platform. She was pretty fired up. I don't know if it gets much better than that."

Julian Guthrie is a San Francisco Chronicle staff writer. E-mail: jguthrie@sfchronicle.com
 














