sales rep threatening to lower a business’s rating if the business didn’t buy advertising. That may surprise conspiracy theorists who love the Yelp extortion meme, but it doesn’t really surprise us. We have a range of controls in place to prevent this sort of thing, and my best guess is that we are far ahead of anyone else in the industry on this issue precisely because we’ve been in the spotlight for so long.  Many of our controls are obvious, like making sure that sales reps don’t have administrative access to post and remove reviews.  Others are a little less obv... (more) What's the solution to San Francisco's housing shortage?   Jeremy Stoppelman, CEO and co-founder of YelpAnswered 75w ago · Upvoted by  Andy Anderson, lives in San Francisco, CA and  Jay Wacker, lived in the Bay Area since 1998Build baby build. NIMBYs have dominated the development conversation in major cities across the nation. This problem is particularly acute in San Francisco where economic and population growth have been robust, but building hasn't remotely kept up. While anti-development groups and voices (often older and wealthier) have long been heard both at various city meetings and through voting, young people often don't vote and aren't particularly well organized. This ultimately means their views aren't fairly represented, which is why I've financially backed SFBARF a pro-renters group that advocate... (more) Are restaurants afraid to be unique and take risks because they're slaves to Yelp reviews?   Jeremy Stoppelman, CEO and co-founder of YelpAnswered 75w agoNate Silver did a study comparing Yelp restaurant ratings to Michelin (which relies on "professional critics") and found them to be quite similar. While Yelp represents a new way to get reliable recommendations on restaurants and other businesses, the idea of publicly critiquing is nothing new and Yelp is unlikely to have had a negative impact on the creativity of chefs and food entrepreneurs. If anything it gives a new and powerful way for non-traditional food providers like food trucks to market themselves since Yelp isn't limited to the high end.5.3k Views · 62 UpvotesWhat do you think of Google My Business listings and reviews?   Jeremy Stoppelman, CEO and co-founder of YelpAnswered 75w agoI think it's a weak product that generally does consumers a disservice. There are much more trusted and reliable ratings/review resources available across the web and mobile and it's a real shame that those options are buried under inferior house-owned Google results. Perhaps it's easiest to show by example. Let's take a popular new(ish) restaurant in San Francisco: Liholiho Yacht Club. Yelp has 683 detailed reviews (our ratings have meaty text explaining what's behind the stars) and over 2000 photos of the food, drinks, and business. Google+ Local's page has 40 "reviews" and 25% of these have... (more) What is Yelp's strategy for addressing businesses that offer incentives for positive reviews?   Jeremy Stoppelman, CEO and co-founder of YelpAnswered 75w agoWe have a number of ways of attacking this. The first line of defense is our recommendation algorithm. It can spot unusual activity and reviews are automatically moved to the not recommended section (off the page). Obviously if you're a business owner providing a valuable incentive for a positive review and those reviews don't stick to your business page, you won't be happy with the outcome and most likely, will stop doing it. We also run sting operations and will post evidence and a prominent "Consumer Alert" on the business' page.4.4k Views · 49 UpvotesHow can Yelp positively affect small business and help them grow?   Jeremy Stoppelman, CEO and co-founder of YelpAnswered 75w ago · Featured in HuffPostYelp levels the playing field between small local businesses and mass chains, allowing them to earn new customers based purely on doing an incredible job day in and out vs. simply having a massive advertising budget. Thanks to Yelp amazing local businesses now get free exposure just for having a great product and delivering good service. We know that 89% of Yelp users spend money at a local business within a week after searching on Yelp. That kind of purchase intent drives dollars directly to small businesses. And if they use the free tools we give them, like responding to reviews, business... (more) MoreMoreShare SessionTwitterFacebook26.9k FollowersShow All         People Asked AboutValuations and other market myths. I’ve been an angel investor for many years and have seen a lot of ups and downs.What it’s like to work at Yelp. I get this question a lot and it’s a great opportunity to talk about our unique culture, and what we’ve done to protect that culture from start-up mode to a 4,000+ person company.What’s happening to the First Amendment? We’re focused on ensuring consumers have online protections for their freedom of speech. Many small businesses don’t like Yelp because they would prefer to keep their unhappy customers quiet, but the First Amendment matters and we’re not backing down. Does Yelp extort small businesses? No, and there’s no amount of money you can pay Yelp to manipulate a business rating. Let’s set the record straight.Rockstar in your late 30s? That’d be nice. Started learning guitar 4 years ago and I’m pretty hooked. Let’s talk about picking up something new and challenging in your adult life, and why I’m not leaving my day job to hit the road anytime soon.Yelp policies and our review algorithm. Designed from day 1 to protect our users and community by ensuring that the content we trust most is what’s informing the spending decisions of millions of consumers around the globe.What’s our beef with Google? And why it’s important - however unpopular - that we challenge the influence and power of one of the world’s most loved brands. The role business leaders (and businesses) can play in solving social issues. From preventing legalized discrimination to promoting fair and affordable housing, and countless other challenges communities are facing, big businesses and their employees can play a key role in driving change.Upcoming SessionsView All  Jeannette Walls, Author of The Glass CastleAnswering Sat at 11:00 AM PDT  Betty Liu, Founder/CEO of RadiateTaking Questions on Insert a dynamic date hereSitemap:#ABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZAbout · Careers · Privacy · Terms · Contact
















