Jeremy Stoppelman: How is Yelp helping small businesses that have a good product but are low rated because of a small number of heavily biased reviews? - QuoraThis page may be out of date. Save your draft before refreshing this page.Submit any pending changes before refreshing this page. Hide this message.QuoraSign In Jeremy Stoppelman Yelp (company) BusinessJeremy Stoppelman: How is Yelp helping small businesses that have a good product but are low rated because of a small number of heavily biased reviews?UpdateCancelPromoted by MetadataAll you need to know to start doing account-based marketing.Create your first account-based marketing campaign using this simple step-by-step guide. Download now!Read More at metadata.ioAnswer Wiki1 Answer  George Weisgerber III, has advised small business owners & entrepreneurs, as well as Fortune 500 CEO'sAnswered 47w agoYelp provides an abundance of support to help small businesses engage with new and existing customers on their platform such as a dashboard filled with analytics, online ordering with no setup fee, a great mobile app, and more. If your business has a poor Yelp rating because of a few biased reviews, here are three steps you can take to improve it:ADDRESS THE “HEAVILY BIASED” REVIEWS: Below are my recommendations for addressing negative reviews, depending on the reason you feel they’re “heavily biased.”The Review Is Fake. Not only is the author not a customer, you believe they are a competitor, disgruntled employee, etc.Respond to the review publicly, with proof that the review is fake. Your reply should be professional & matter-of-fact. Take the highroad and don’t write anything that reflects negatively on you or your business. Remember you’re composing this response to inform your customers; not to insult your competition or former employee.Flag the review, by logging into either the Yelp for Business Owners mobile app or website, and clicking “report this review.” Provide as much relevant and factual information for the moderator that will be evaluating the validity of your claim. Follow up with an email to feedback@yelp.com.The Review is From An Actual Customer. Although you feel the review is totally biased and not-true; it was written by a one of your leads or customers.Send a private message to the customer who left the review. Respond diplomatically and thank the reviewer for their feedback, perhaps this is a simple misunderstanding that can be rectified, and possibly lead to the customer leaving an updated review.If that doesn’t work, respond publicly. Potential customers will get to read your side of the story, and see that your business is responsive to feedback.PROACTIVELY CREATE OPPORTUNITIES FOR POSITIVE REVIEWS. Now that you’ve addressed the BAD, you can start focusing on the GOOD :)Place a "Find us on Yelp" sign near the cash wrap, or a sticker in your window.Update your email signature by adding a yelp icon with a link to your page. Followed by, “the best compliment is a 5-star review”If you see a customer check-in on Yelp, Twitter, Foursquare or any other platform: Leave a comment thanking them for stopping by, and let them know you appreciate any feedback they can provide, followed by a link to your yelp page ;)KEEP EM’ COMING BACK FOR MORE A Harvard Study found that a one-star increase in a business’s Yelp rating, leads to 5–9% more revenue. So don’t stop, just because you’ve gotten a few good reviews to balance out those “heavily biased” ones. Be sure to respond to all new reviews ASAP and follow these three quick steps to attract new customers to your business via YelpMake sure you business’s address, hours, phone #, and website info are updatedUpload enticing images and videos of your businessYelp allows your business to be listed in up to three categories. Take advantage of all three. For instance, if you have a pizzeria that serves other dishes, and offers catering; be sure you’re listed under Italian Food and Catering, not just Pizza.I understand how frustrating it can be to read negative things about your business, especially heavily biased reviews. You didn’t invest your blood, sweat, tears and treasure into your small business, so some knucklehead could go disparage you online. Remember why you did though, to build something that’s yours, to do what you love, and to serve those customers who love your food, service, clothing, etc.George Weisgerber III www.localangel.nyc248 ViewsPromoted by ToptalGreat developers and designers are hard to find.Let Toptal match you with the top 3% of developers and designers for your next project. No-risk trial.Sign Up at toptal.comView More AnswersRelated QuestionsJeremy Stoppelman: What evidence do Yelp's opponents cite in arguing that Yelp extorts small businesses?Jeremy Stoppelman: How does Yelp's culture differ from other major internet companies?Jeremy Stoppelman: What are Yelp's plans in the next 2 years to create shareholder value?How would Yelp convince a small business that has already accumulated a lot of reviews to pay?Jeremy Stoppelman: Yelp reviews can crush a business without any semblance of fact to them. Does Yelp have plans to address this issue?What are some potential low-cost businesses that can be started and operated by a teenager?Jeremy Stoppelman: Do you think Yelps business model is sustainable? How are you thinking of changing it to monetize your large audience bette...Jeremy Stoppelman: How did Yelp acquire businesses to gain traction?Jeremy Stoppelman: Whats new that yelp is working on and is Yelp also trying to develop some other product?Jeremy Stoppelman: Why don’t you implement a user search for business, that way they can tell if a current/potential customer uses yelp?Jeremy Stoppelman: Why are Yelp reviews not shown for local businesses on Google Maps? Are there plans for bringing them there?Jeremy Stoppelman: What's the long term strategy of Yelp? Are you planning to foray into any new lines of business?Jeremy Stoppelman: Is Yelp the first business you started, how many were not successful before Yelp?What is your best small business advice?Jeremy Stoppelman: How can I land an interview with Yelp?Related QuestionsJeremy Stoppelman: What evidence do Yelp's opponents cite in arguing that Yelp extorts small businesses?Jeremy Stoppelman: How does Yelp's culture differ from other major internet companies?Jeremy Stoppelman: What are Yelp's plans in the next 2 years to create shareholder value?How would Yelp convince a small business that has already accumulated a lot of reviews to pay?Jeremy Stoppelman: Yelp reviews can crush a business without any semblance of fact to them. Does Yelp have plans to address this issue?What are some potential low-cost businesses that can be started and operated by a teenager?Jeremy Stoppelman: Do you think Yelps business model is sustainable? How are you thinking of changing it to monetize your large audience bette...Jeremy Stoppelman: How did Yelp acquire businesses to gain traction?Jeremy Stoppelman: Whats new that yelp is working on and is Yelp also trying to develop some other product?Jeremy Stoppelman: Why don’t you implement a user search for business, that way they can tell if a current/potential customer uses yelp?Sitemap:#ABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZAbout · Careers · Privacy · Terms · Contact


