How Yelp C.E.O. Jeremy Stoppelman Created a Revolutionary Product






























	Serving up this steaming pile of

	Celebrity Gossip
	Gay Politics
	Gay News
	and Pointless Bitchery

	Since 1995









Toggle navigation















How Yelp C.E.O. Jeremy Stoppelman Created a Revolutionary Product
He was just another gangly Web 2.0 kid with a good job in Silicon Valley (at PayPal) and a big dream: in his case, to launch an online successor to the Yellow Pages. But something funny happened shortly after Jeremy Stoppelman’s project, Yelp, went live: its users embraced the site’s “Write a review” feature to a degree far greater than anticipated. A few weeks of hasty re-coding later, Yelp was reconfigured to make reviewing its raison d’être, and Stoppelman has never looked back. Ten years after its founding, Yelp is the Web’s premier site and app for customer reviews—not just of restaurants, but of shops, kiosks, food trucks, parks, bus lines, funeral homes, D.M.V. offices, and even human attractions. (The Naked Cowboy in Times Square was averaging four stars out of five at press time.) Herewith, some info gleaned from a meandering conversation with the Yelp C.E.O., who turns 37 this November.HE IS himself an avid Yelper, reviewing under the profile name Big Papa. He has waxed enthusiastic over the Renaissance Salon in his current hometown of San Francisco (“My last haircut generated mucho complimentos” ) and panned Frankfurt’s airport (an “authentic interpretation of Dante’s Inferno” ).AMONG THE happiest discoveries he has made by perusing Yelp reviews is the existence of the Seward Street Slides, in San Francisco’s Castro district. “It’s basically these two concrete slides in a quiet, residential neighborhood,” he says. “You zip down them sitting on top of flattened cardboard boxes. I’d be curious to learn the history of these slides, because they’re, like, not at all safe.”HE INITIALLY resisted the push to name his company Yelp, because, to him, it sounded like “a sad cry for help.” He preferred the name Yocal (rhyming with “local” ).HE GREW up in the Virginia suburbs of Washington, D.C., the son of a securities lawyer and a teacher, and attended Langley High School, just down the road from the headquarters of the C.I.A. Among his schoolmates were a son of Antonin Scalia’s and some kids who were curiously vague about what their parents did for a living.HE IS—notwithstanding the fact that Google’s autocomplete function suggests the words “Jeremy Stoppelman Indian” when you enter his name into the search field—a Jewish American of European ancestry who attended a Reform temple as a child and had a Bar Mitzvah. He attributes the frequent misperception of his ethnicity to his “black hair and dark skin tone.”HE PLAYED tennis as a youth and was often told that he looked like Pete Sampras.HIS FIRST computer—his family’s, actually—was an Amiga 2000, a little-remembered late-80s high-end P.C. with “unbelievable sound and graphics capabilities” that, to this day, he feels doesn’t get its due.HIS YOUNGER brother, Michael, is Yelp’s vice president in charge of engineering. His older brother, Andy, two years his senior, died abruptly on the eve of his high-school graduation, in 1993, of a rare heart-rhythm disorder. That experience, Jeremy says, made him realize that “life is very short and you have to make the most of it.”HE IS frequently vilified by critics who claim that Yelp is a protection racket whose sales representatives shake down small-business owners, offering better placement of positive reviews (and/or the burying of negative reviews) in exchange for ad purchases—a charge that Stoppelman flatly denies, noting that all the lawsuits brought against Yelp to this effect have been dismissed.HE WAS called a “scumbag,” a “dick,” and “full of shit,” among other things, when he participated in a Reddit Ask Me Anything session last year. He did not respond in kind.HE ACCEPTS the invective hurled his way as the cost of creating a “disruptive, game-changing service or product,” likening the heat Yelp takes to that felt by Airbnb (vis-à-vis the hotel industry) and Uber (vis-à-vis the taxicab industry).HE HAS met three current or former heads of state: two U.S. presidents, Barack Obama and Bill Clinton, and the Taoiseach of Ireland, Enda Kenny.by Anonymousreply 610/02/2014


That's uh-maaaaazing!by Anonymousreply 110/01/2014


